segments.text: pleasure today of chatting with Davis Ford at his office in Austin about his recollections of life as a student at Texas A&M.
Why did you attend A&M in the first place?
Well, my father was an A&M man, class of 1926, and so I grew up with an A&M ethic.
Went to football games when I was a kid.
And so I was preordained to go there, and it was never in question.
We lived in Lubbock, and of course grew up in the shadows of Texas Tech, but I was in A&M all the way, never in question.
What were your earliest memories of visiting A&M?
Well, I came up there on a high school day and brought five of my friends, best friends from Lubbock, who never really had any background at A&M whatsoever.
I was...
This is going to sound a bit ironic.
I was amazed at how green and pretty it was in the springtime compared to Lubbock.
In those days in Lubbock, you couldn't even see 10 feet ahead because of the sandstorms that we had back in the 50s.
And I thought the whole world was hot and sandy and dust storms until I went down to College Station.
I said, this is the most beautiful place I've ever seen.
Some people kind of laugh at it today, but it was green and lush and trees and all.
So I said, man, it's a pretty setting.
And...
We stayed in the dorms with corps members and all very impressed.
So all five of the non-A&M background high school classmates of mine went to A&M, as long as it was me.
So we have a total of six in Lubbock that year.
When you came to enroll, how did you get there?
Did you come on the train or the bus or the car?
No.
Nobody really had cars back in those days except for rich kids, of which I was not.
My dad was a farmer, kind of middle class sort of guy.
But two of my friends were pretty wealthy kids and they had cars.
So six of us piled in two cars with all our trunks and luggage and go from Lubbock to College Station.
Describe what you brought with you.
We were all a little bit nervous because we knew about the Corps.
I had a little bit more understanding what the weight of this than my five high school colleagues did.
We just bought just kind of rudimentary stuff.
I'll tell you what we didn't bring.
We didn't bring golf clubs or tennis rackets.
They were just kind of the bare essentials.
We were all kind of, grew up in Lubbock, had the Lubbock ethic.
No place in the world better being raised than Lubbock in the 1950s.
So we just bought kind of the typical things.
No books, no tennis rackets, no golf clubs, just our basic stuff.
Describe the campus physically when you got there.
It was hot.
And, of course, we were from kind of the dry part of the state, and we just sweated profusely.
I could not believe how uncomfortable it was with the humidity.
We were not used to that.
I'm getting this later probably, but it was not a freshman privilege to have a fan in your room.
Of course, none of the dorms were air-conditioned.
The only air-conditioned building was the Cushing Library on campus to Mount Olive.
Right.
But describe the campus physically in terms of what buildings were where.
Yeah.
The dominant buildings, of course, were the Old Main, MSC,
And then all the dorms that were built back in, I guess, the 30s, that was kind of the prominent place.
The old President's Home, the old frame President's Home over by Spacer was still there.
And it was not a pretty campus.
It was a pretty setting, not really a pretty campus to speak of.
There was no coordination of the buildings and all.
It was enrollment, as I recall, in my freshman year, was about 6,000 or 7,000 students, virtually all cadet corps.
How did you feel that you were treated as a new arrival?
Horrible.
Horrible.
I thought I was pretty much a stud in high school.
I had my hair and a lot of girlfriends.
And I grew up in Lubbock High School doing things kids did.
And over the day we hunted and fished and chased women and played football.
Lubbock High School had been state champion for two or three years.
The last four years we were the big football power, draw 25,000 people to a game.
And Texas Tech was not much of a football power in those days, so Lubbock High School was the place.
So we thought we were big stuff.
Came down to A&M, shaved my head, and I was miserable.
Did you go through any kind of pre-class, pre-academic boot camp or any experience before?
It wasn't exactly boot camp.
They had what they called fish week.
So the upperclassmen were not on campus.
Describe fish week.
The only people that were there were our CO and first sergeant.

our outfits and it was just orientation there was no no hazing or anything it was just kind of an orientation of kind of stark setting but we were all nervous about when the upperclassmen particularly sophomores would get there a week hence so we were nervous but fish week was just more like any college orientation buying books getting issued from the army or our military uh apparel
things like that.
How'd you get assigned?
How did you?
We had some requests on what outfit we went in.
I'd heard, I was in the Ordinance Corps, I'd heard that the Ordinance Corps was one of the better outfits on the campus and it had a lot of technical people, engineers, things like that.
So it was, that was, I just requested it.
And what was its identifying number and letter?
A Ordinance.
There was only one Ordinance outfit.
Did it have a nickname?
I don't think it did.
Ordinance was,
I heard this was the case before I got there, when I got in there.
It was more, probably had more serious students than a lot of our colleagues, the jocks and infantry.
Right, and you all were housed, your unit was housed where?
Dorm 7.
And that's in the quote, new dorm area?
New dorm area.
That was my freshman year was in Dorm 7.
Was your roommate a special person in your life?
Interesting.
I phoned him Stacha, S-T-A-C-H-A, Anton Stacha.
Good boy, from Clifton, Texas.
And never, probably about the most provincial guy you've ever met in your life.
Just a real country boy.
Good guy.
And did freshman roommates have a nickname then?
Oh, yeah, official name.
Same as it is now.
And that friendship, has that proved lasting?
Yeah, Statue is one of those guys who really was not college material, but he made it.
Like a lot of freshmen who came into court at that time were really country boys.
As you know, Andy was considered to be kind of the poor boy at school at that time.
There's a lot of truth to that.
It wasn't universally true, but there's some truth to it.
I've lost contact with Statue.
I don't know really whatever happened to him.
My next roommate, my sophomore and junior years, is and was a lifetime friend of Jack McCrary, who was the best man at my wedding.
M-C-C-R-A-R-Y.
So he was the roommate that I developed a strong and lasting friendship with.
I had dinner with him a week ago.
make believe that I had never heard what it was like to be a freshman in the Corps of Cadets.
Describe it.
It was, I guess it was kind of a shock deal because it was, it was austere.
They shaved your heads and when they shave your heads your love life ceases totally.
You, we had to make 21 formations
I had the unfortunate talent of being a good typist, so I was the perk.
Every hour was filled.
I was very unhappy first semester.
Also, I had no background in engineering.
My dad was a farmer.
Came from three generations of farmers.
really went broke in the 50s because of the drought that we had.
He was in Catalan and farming and so it was a shock really to get into engineering and just academically plus the Corps of Cadets so it was it was traumatic.
Describe if you will a typical weekday of routine what time to get up?
Yeah it was regimented.
It was regimented.
It was
We had first call at 6.30.
We had formation, breakfast, then class, intramurals in the afternoon.
Then we had study hall from 7.30 to 10.30, lights out at 10.30.
So it was a very mechanical, rigid type of a situation.
Obviously, it's not a military school.
It was a state school.
So I don't want to imply it was like West Point or the Naval Academy, but it was pretty close to it.
Let's see, did you go to, you ate in Duncan?
I ate in Duncan every year except my senior year.
Did y'all march to all three meals?
Yes.
Did you fall out and go?
Yes.
Describe a typical meal for a fish.
You know, it's interesting.
The most
I guess the big protest of people who didn't know what to expect, like my five friends from Lubbock High School, was that we paid for this meal where we could never eat dessert.
They would have cush questions, which were impossible to answer, particularly when it was good cush.
If it was bad cush, it was easy questions.
So we never ate dessert.
Bushes sat erect and had a certain protocol as freshmen in the mess hall, which everything kind of had a purpose to it, but it was not a casual meal like I had today.
Can you describe for me some of the dining hall food slang?
Oh, gosh.
Some of it was profane.
Most of it was just kush, was dessert.
Gunwaden was bread.
I don't remember all of them, but everything had a name to it.
What about some of the beverages?
Gosh, I'm not sure.
Milk?
I'm not sure I remember.
I recall others.
There were words that weren't quite as cute as some of the others.
Beans?
I don't recall that.
Everything had a name.
If you called it by the wrong name, they wouldn't even pass it to you.
They'd ignore you.
And as a fish, what was your task at the table?
Just to serve up the classroom.
You were strictly there just to fulfill man's basic needs.
Just need to have food, but that was about it.
There was no enjoyment.
As you look back on it, what general evaluation would you give the quality of food?
Oh, I thought the quality of food was good.
Yeah, it was, you know, it was not the health food that we have today.
But I thought the food was good.
We all, nobody ever went hungry.
Let's see, can you describe any of the
pranks that you freshmen may have played on anybody?
Well, I tell you, we're too afraid to do that early.
But after we kind of got into the situation, taking the second semester of our freshman year, we started doing pretty wild things to upperclassmen.
Please describe some of them.
Well, one which stands in my memory, which will be in my memory to the day I die, was there was one upperclassman that we didn't like, not because he was hard on us, he was just, he was slovenly.
And we didn't like him.
So, uh, during the Christmas break, my freshman year, my roommate or my good friend, Jack McCreary, and I went over, they were building the Sabre motel.
So on highway six at the time, Jack McCreary came from a very wealthy family.
He was a little extraordinary for Aggies.
He had a big car, big trunk.
So we went over there that night.
Uh, I think the statute of limitations has passed.
So I think I can speak frankly.
And we took a lot of the Austin stone that they were building the Sabre Motel out of and put it in this car.
And then went over and bought some water, sand.
And we did a real nice bricklaying job of the front of his door in the hall.
And I think it was dorm seven.
And so when he came, and then we put a big I believe we put a cat in there and gave the cat a lot of food.
And then bricked it up.

And when he came back from the Christmas holidays, he had a beautiful floor-to-ceiling brick wall in front of his door and a cat who had enjoyed the luxury of an unlimited supply of food and no sandbox in his room.
That's probably about the worst thing we did.
Oh, that's a good one.
A good one.
And I don't think to this day ever knew who did it.
Let's see.
Take me to class now.
How did you...
Did you all go to class as a group or anything?
What did you wear to class?
And what kind of behavior did you and your colleagues practice in class?
Well, we were in summer uniform or winter uniform.
Summer uniform was just khaki.
Winter uniform was a little bit different type.
I forgot the material right now.
And then we sometimes would go in fatigues.
We could go in fatigues when we had laps.
Of course, I'd be an engineering major.
We had a lot of labs.
But you couldn't go in fatigues to class.
You had to wear fatigues only when there was a lab involved.
Again, I kind of went into a shock.
I had no engineering or technical background.
That's kind of a sidebar.
When I was a junior or senior in high school and my dad was having such a tough time in the cattle business, I asked a friend of mine's father,
about engineering because he was a very successful consulting engineer.
So he became kind of my very mentor in encouraging me to get into engineering.

And he told me, he said, go to A&M, get an engineering degree, and then go to the Army and go to Corps of Engineers, work as a civilian for their training program, and come back to Lubbock and work for me.
I did every one of those signs.
So the engineering, to get into engineering was kind of a shock to me.
I get a little nostalgic sometimes when I talk about it, but it's kind of a shock.
But once I got through the first three or four weeks, it became pretty easy for me.
A fairly significant question.
Describe the role that some of the significant teachers, advisors played in your development.
That's not too much my freshman year.
We had good instructors for freshman year, but like any university, probably you had your younger professors, assistant professors coming in and teaching freshmen.
As I went through the teaching process, professors certainly made a lasting impression on me.
I can name two or four today.
Please do.
Doc Harrington, a hydraulics professor, was really extraordinary.
Dr. Nederman thought reinforced concrete, who later became the president of the University of Texas at Arlington.
Wendell Nederman.
Wendell Nederman.
Outstanding professor.
Those were the two who I thought was most impressive.
There's a third one, though, who was in his senior
probably a senior tenure as a full professor, well known, named Spencer Buchanan, who taught me soil mechanics.
And again, we didn't know the profession at that time.
We were undergraduates.
We didn't know the real depth and strength of the profession.
But it was obvious to me that he was extraordinary.
He had published books.
He was well known in the profession.
It meant more to me in graduate school than it did as an undergraduate, because we just wanted to get out of school and weren't really sensitive to all
the world of specialty professions, but Spencer Buchanan, I would say those three were extraordinary.
Did you have Alphabet Thompson?
I did not.
JGH?
Mom Semang?
I knew Semang.
I did not have him.
Can you, do you remember any other faculty nicknames?
Oh, good gosh, yes.
Please share those.
Well, Joe Sorrells was my sanitary engineering professor.
We called him Fecal Joe.
Joe Orr was my surveying professor.
We called him Shaky Joe.
We were pretty low class back in those days.
He had an affliction where his hand shook quite a bit.
In fact, we had Junction as an adjunct.
We spent about six weeks out there with Shaky Joe.
Oh, we'll want to talk about Junction.
Oh, I'll tell you a lot about Junction.
It was a great part of my career.
We called Dr. Ned Rivets, because he was an instructor and so forth.
Those were the nicknames.
We had nicknames for most of them, unless they were pretty straight.
For example, Doc Harrington.
So lovable.
I was commanding officer in my outfit in my senior year and making my faculty advisor.
Remember any in math or chemistry or biology?
No, again, math and chemistry and physics and thermo were adjuncts to my profession.
So you didn't really relate to those professors.
That's just something you had to do.
Double E, thermo.
math, for example, calculus, about as high as we went in this engineering in those days.
Those are people, those are just things that we had to endure.
I do remember my physics professor.
It was in 1956.
I'm not even sure I remember his name.
He was a Hungarian refugee who had just escaped the last minute from the Hungarian Revolution.
A real young fellow, a brilliant guy.
But I remember our big complaint was we could hardly understand his English.
Obviously, he was picking up English, but he was a great physicist.
And what was his
I don't remember his name.
I just remember that he was the first professor I ever had who I had a hard time understanding, which is a kind of commonplace situation today.
But most of my non-track courses were just, you just endured it.
You had to do it.
I didn't have any trouble in it.
To whom did you turn for academic advice?
Who was your key counselor advisor?
That's kind of interesting, Haskell, because I really didn't seek much academic advice all the way through school.
The first three or four or five weeks in engineering were kind of a shock, but then I could grasp it pretty easily.
And once I got into that rhythm, I just really knew where I was going, and I just didn't really seek much help from any academic advisor.
It was there.
I just didn't seek it.
Now, who was the dean then, dean of engineering?
I'm going to say John Calhoun.
I think that's correct.
John Calhoun, which we never saw.
I just knew who he was.
It's interesting because I got to know him later in academic life.
A fellow named Wright was the head of the Civil Engineering Department.
We hardly ever saw him.
The people who got pretty high up never spent much time, nor did we seek much time with undergraduates.
All right, let's go back to Junction.
Tell me all about Junction.
Great experience.
Junction was an adjunct of A&M, made famous, of course, by Mayor Bryant.
And it was a kind of Texas Hill country and a beautiful place.
And we went out there for six weeks.
The geologists and the civil engineers went to Junction.
And when did you go?
It was in the summertime.
And it was a six-week, pretty intense surveying camp.
The geologists went out there to look at the subsurface strata and so forth.
We went out there to learn surveying.
Shakey Joe Orr was our professor.
He was the only professor out there.
And it was really a great experience.
We had a lot of fun because we lived in these kind of semi-tents and all fell in love with Junction Girls.
This was in June?
This was probably July.
I think they had two semis.
Also, they had a freshman orientation area.
Some freshmen would go to Junction for orientation.
I never did.
We had freshmen, geologists, of course when Baird Bryant was there, one football can, but I think the Southwest Conference had to rule that out after he was there.
But the footprints were there.
I mean, we went through the same junction they went through, except we just didn't have to work as hard under Baird.
We'd shakey-joke a little easier than Baird Bryant.
But it was just great.
We had fish on the weekends.
We all had girlfriends.
A lot of us had girlfriends in junction.
All the junction high school boys had this because when Aggies came in, we just kind of took over the...
the female stock there.
And where, on a Saturday night, where did y'all go for a good time?
We'd go country and western dancing.
In Junction?
In Junction or some honky-tonk close by.
I had lots of honky-tonk.
How did y'all get back and forth?
Most of us had cars.
Most of us had cars.
This was our junior year.
Two of our junior and senior years, I recall.
And so we would go to all these little outlying towns, Sonora, Junction, places like that that was on them.
And
Of course, being a West Texan, I'd put on my boots and my cowboy hat and stuff, left arm.
We'd go out there and dance.
All right, now, and you did not, the summer was not in Aggie Corps uniform or Corps.
Oh, no.
And see, this time we had gone through kind of a weeding out process.
We were all, we became more civilianized, I guess, as you go through the Corps and you get through your sophomore year.
And we were on kind of a degree track, starting to think about the future.
So Junction was just a great time.
Not going to summer camp, summer boys camp, except we got six hour or five hour
credit course.
Had a lot of good experiences.
It's kind of a side issue.
Shakey Joe had a red pickup.

And in describing surveying notes, you always, when you get a certain surveying point and you locate it in the coordinates and elevation, you describe it, describe it so subsequent people can come out and find it.
And all of a sudden, we put down our notes, this turning point or this benchmark is located 4.5 yards away from a red pickup truck.
The Shakey Joe would always come and check on us.
Also, we had a, shortly after the Korean War, we had a mountain called Heartbreak Ridge.
What you had to do is run a string of levels to get the elevation up to the, you'd go all the way up, and it'd take all day long.
There's old surveying equipment, so we'd have to establish the elevation at the top of the mountain.
And of course, everybody knew what it was from past classes.
So it was pretty easy, and if you didn't get within a tenth of a foot, then you had to run it on Saturday.
Well, that would have disrupted our dancing and our social plans with the Junction High School girls, so we all wanted to make sure that we got it.
Well, to make sure that nobody cheated, Shakey Joe would take the last shot on the rod to the transit to make sure that we couldn't pencil it in.
Not that we would have done that, but it was a temptation to do that because we all knew what the automation was.
So he would stay up there, he'd crawl up there, leave his red pickup truck at the bottom of Heartbreak Hill and go up there to the top and take the last shot to make sure that you came in with a 10.
75% of us got it right.
I see.
On Junction, two more questions.
Physically, what was there at the adjunct?
They had a cafeteria, kind of a mess hall.
Really nice.
These were permanent buildings with screens and permanent roofs at that time.
So there was kind of cabins which were all wood and screened at the top and it wouldn't
So that was about it.
We had a, I think we had a swimming pool.
There was a, a river ran through it and always had water.
So it was, it was not luxurious, but it was adequate.
All right.
And now looking back, evaluate what that experience was for you as an engineer.
We had a lot of bonding going on.
We had some good friends out there.
We had surveying parties before each.
So we worked as, and we did a lot of pretty advanced surveying at that time using that technology.
It was a great practical experience.
In those days, part of engineering was surveying.
And I did a lot of surveying in my first part of my professional career.
And probably we had the best surveying education of any university in the country at that time, right?
College at that time.
So it was a great experience.
It was a lot of fun.
We learned a good science.
We learned to shoot the stars and establish true north and all those kind of things.
Shoot polaris is what we called it.
So it was a big-time deal.
I was a little bit saddened when A&M transferred the country over to Texas Tech, but I didn't know any of the details, but it was a great part of my education.
All right, let's go back into the routine.
What was it like to be a sophomore at A&M compared to being a freshman?
Well, a little bit more of a human being.
Let your hair grow out.
Start dating girls again.
We're getting a little bit more confidence in our curriculum.
And I was, again, in a company in a,
ROTC unit that was working with all technical people, engineers.
So we made a lot of fun at that time.
We were only really scholars and a whole bunch.
Everybody else would flunk out of engineering and go to business.
So we called engineering pre-prisoners administration.
That's what we all called it.
But the engineering curriculum was tough.
But we, at that time, when you're a sophomore, you figure out you want to graduate.
We could handle it.
Corps was our leisure.
It was just more of the, you got to look at more of the so-called college life and away from the more rigid discipline that goes with freshman.
All right, and when you, what were the expected, I'll say, rules of classroom behavior?
How did you expect?
Well, there were really no rules.
It was just, no, there was, in my whole career at A&M, I don't remember any misbehavior in the classroom.
None, zero.
I don't remember any rules and guidelines that never entered our mind.
There'd be any classroom behavior situations.
Did y'all expect to go to class regularly?
Oh, yeah.
I mean, we wouldn't get out of school.
I mean, that wasn't any question, not going to class.
One time we'd cut class, maybe on a Friday afternoon on one of our easier courses, and normally the professor's pretty lean in that regard, but cutting class was just unheard of.
Do you have any recollection of how much it cost
for your, per year?
Absolutely, almost to the dollar.
Please describe that.
My, virtually all of my classmates were not subsidized.
There were no scholarships.
There were scholarships available, but very few of us won scholarships.
I could make enough in the summertime working as an intern consulting engineer for my mentor that I mentioned previously.
I could make about $1,000 a summer.
It was all saved because I lived at home.
I worked in Lubbock.
And it cost me about $1,000 a year.
So I think I probably got $300 or $400 of help from my father.
But I ended up out of A&M for a total cost of about $4,000.
I had no debt.
And a college degree.
So it was a pretty simple thing.
Now, if you didn't work in the summer, you'd be subsidized, obviously.
Now, very few students worked.
A few worked as waiters, and we really respected those guys.
But very few, you couldn't be in the Corps and work.
You just couldn't do it, unless you were a waiter.
Activities on the campus, the Y, the MSC, and so forth, what were the places where you all went for extracurricular events?
I did not get involved in any extracurricular events my freshman year.
I had all I could handle.
And I really wasn't oriented that way my freshman year.
I just wanted to survive.
Sophomore year, a little bit.
But junior and senior year, I became much more oriented toward extracurricular events.
I was very active in SCOMA, Student Council on National Affairs.
We had a lot of fun going to pick up students at North Filch on the train coming up all over the country.
MSC, there were some activities primarily through the MSC.
I did not get involved with the Y at all.
We had what was called the Student Chapter of American Society of Civil Engineers, which I got involved with.
But most of us volunteers was great experience.
So those are most of the activities in which I became involved.
We also had a student body of the entity in the Army called the American Ordnance Association, which I spent some time with.
Do you remember any famous visitors or celebrities that you saw or heard?
Well, let me tell you just kind of a funny story.
The answer is not really.
And let me underscore that story.
I went to the, my wife and I went to the opening of the Bush Library.
We're just about six rows from the front.
And we saw every living president, except President Reagan, all living first ladies, John Major, Doug Valenza, on and on and on.
And of course, a lot of...
Corps members were heavily involved in this.
So I was talking to one of the corps members after this was over, and I said, I hope you recognize what a historic day this was.
And all these famous people on this campus.
I said, in my four years at A&M, all I saw was a drunk ex-county commissioner.
And there's a lot of truth to that.
I'm just making a funny story, but there's a lot of truth to that.
I don't remember any really famous people.
The only one I recall is Schooner.
We had Hubert Humphrey come down and talk to us.
And I remember his speakers before and after him made a lot of fun of him.
As you know, he's very loquacious.
And, in fact, the one after him said, you know, when Senator Humphrey comes up and talks, you don't know what he's going to say.
When he talks, you don't know what he said.
And when he gets through talking, you forget everything he said.
So they made a lot of fun of him.
He was a very, actually a very articulate guy.
He's about the only one I remember of any note that in my four years, of course, President Eisenhower had been there before, General Eisenhower.
And we had probably famous people before and after, but during my tenure,
very few people of international note that I recall.
Did you have any interaction, acquaintance with Wayne Stark?
Oh, certainly.
Describe him.
Well, Wayne Stark, just again, one of those men of history.
Wayne had a real propensity for students and picking out bright students who he considered to be bright and acting as a mentor to bring them along.
In fact, it's hard to talk about Wayne without getting a bit emotional.
I mean...
I share your feeling about him.
I think Wayne was right.
